node.text:
I posted this on my stories yesterday, and I thought it would be good to give it a more permanent space on my feed after the response I received.⁣
⁣
Unlearning toxic hustle culture can be really, really difficult. ⁣
⁣
I don’t know about you, but I grew up with people all around me glorifying working nonstop and getting little sleep. Biting off more than you can chew and also feeling exhausted were worn like badges of honor. It felt like a competition - who can feel the most like shit? 💩 ⁣
⁣
As a result, I felt an incredible amount of pressure to always do more, more, more, and I would find myself feeling overwhelming guilty any time I dared to take a bit of rest. ⁣
⁣
Can we flip the script? ⁣
⁣
Can we celebrate actually taking care of ourselves, getting adequate rest, and not running on fumes? ⁣
⁣
Honestly, I’m at my best when I sleep lots, eat ample nutritious food, and give myself regular downtime. ⁣
⁣
Looking after your mental health and prioritizing self-care can be in the “in” thing to do. 🥰

node.title: You’re not better off for suffering more

node.text:
This is not how things should be. ⁣
⁣
I don’t want to be another person who’s aware of inappropriate behavior, knowing it’s wrong, and still do nothing except shake my head in disapproval and move on. ⁣
⁣
In this video, I briefly touch on some events that have transpired relating to @the_issn over the past 8 days. ⁣
⁣
In addition to sexism and fat phobia displayed by the social media pages linked through the ISSN website, the feeds have been included personal, bigoted views posted by Dr. Jose Antonio that are not reflective of ISSN alleged values. ⁣
⁣
Sincerely, I was hoping that it would not come to this. I made numerous attempts to make it clear privately to ISSN leadership over the past week that posting a diversity statement on the website was not enough. It’s felt performative; this is not true allyship. ⁣
⁣
What’s happened instead is what appears to be a quiet clean-up job. But many individuals, including members like myself and other onlookers who have been watching these events unfold, have been looking to ISSN leadership to address what’s happened head on. We want to know where you stand.⁣
⁣
“The ISSN does not discriminate on the basis of race, color, creed, religion, sex, gender expression, age, national origin/ancestry, disability, marital status, sexual orientation, or military status, in any of its activities or operations.” ⁣
⁣
Do you stand by this statement, even when it’s being violated by individuals at the top of your own organization? ⁣
⁣
None of this had to be this way. All of this could have been a near non-issue, and I would have gained tremendous respect for the ISSN had they responded to this directly and swiftly. But we’ve waited and waited with little to nothing changed.⁣
⁣
I expected more. ⁣
⁣
ISSN, your silence has been so, so loud. ⁣
⁣
And because you have been quiet, I am making noise. ⁣
⁣
Please show @amandahowellhealth your support. She has been one of the only individuals brave enough to call out  inappropriate behavior displayed by ISSN social media and has been blocked and ignored by the leaders. ⁣
⁣
#InternationalSocietyOfSportsNutrition #ISSN

Not gonna lie, I have never taken so many long pauses while filming a video (I’ve cut most of them out). This one really got me in the feels…. 😢💔⁣
⁣
As I mentioned on my stories yesterday, opening up about my eating disorder history can be pretty painful. In some ways, I at times feel as though I’m re-living the many sad moments of my teens and 20s. But I also believe that sharing my story can help others. ⁣
⁣
The purpose of this video is threefold. I want to: ⁣
⁣
✨take the shame and stigma out of eating disorder struggles. ⁣
✨shed more light on how debilitating eating disorders can be. ⁣
✨normalize admitting when you’re not okay and normalizing getting help. ⁣
⁣
I also continue to share more about what this experience was like for me and some factors that helped me get better. ⁣
⁣
NationalEatingDisorders.org ⁣
⁣
#NEDAwareness #edrecovery

In today’s video, I respond to some comments that a user made against my argument that we shouldn’t be labeling foods as “good” or “bad”, nor do we need to completely forbid nutrient-devoid foods from our diet. This individual cited a 2019 study by Murray. ⁣
⁣
This person’s argument is one that many, many try to make. I’ll show you why this argument is invalid. ⁣
⁣
This particular study aimed to quantify the impact of “suboptimal” dietary intake on non-communicable diseases mortality and morbidity. ⁣
⁣
Researchers examined numerous dietary factors, including mean daily consumption/intake of fruits, vegetables, whole grains, nuts and seeds, and more. They found that poor dietary habits at the population level was a risk factor for several health outcomes. These findings are not surprising, and I also don’t disagree with them. ⁣
⁣
In the Discussions section, they wrote, “suboptimal diet is responsible for more deaths than any other risks globally, including tobacco smoking,” but as I mention in my video, this doesn’t mean that having one donut equates to a “bad diet,” nor does it equate to being worse than smoking. ⁣
⁣
Unfortunately, this paper does not support this individual’s argument. Their mistakes include: ⁣
⁣
❌assuming that one food in isolation provides an accurate picture of the quality of overall diet ⁣
❌assuming that eating a donut means that your fruit, vegetable, legume etc. consumption is low (in reality, you can both eat a donut and still consume plenty of nutrient-dense foods throughout the day) ⁣
❌taking one statement made in a research paper and making a huge logical leap that does not work ⁣
❌resorting to appeal to authority at the end⁣
⁣
Should we be encouraging a diet high in nutrients? Absolutely. ⁣
And should we also be teaching people not to demonize foods? For sure. ⁣
Is it okay to have some nutrient-devoid foods every now and then and still have an overall high quality diet while maintaining a healthy relationship with food? You bet. ⁣
⁣
All three of these statements can be true at the same time. ⁣
⁣
One donut - or two donuts, or three donuts - does not a bad diet make. ⁣
⁣
Don’t miss the forest for the trees. ⁣

⚠️TW: EATING DISORDER, CHRONIC ILLNESS⚠️

Earlier this week, @bdccarpenter and I sat down to further discuss the misconception that leaner does not always mean you’re healthier. Both he and I have personal experiences of this statement being the furthest thing from the truth. 

For me, I became anorexic and bulimic at the age of 14, then continued to struggle with bulimia and then only binge eating for about 8 years afterwards. 

For Benji, his Crohn’s disease saw him rapidly shedding 50lbs off his frame in a short period of time with barely enough energy to get out of bed. 

Judging by the many many messages I’ve received from my followers, I think it’s safe to say that a lot of you can relate and have had similar experiences. 

Suffice to say, we are both much healthier (not to mention happier) now with more body fat on our frames than before. 

Because yes, there is more to health than body fat and body size. 

My mental peace with food, exercise, and my body is everything now. I’ve worked hard to get back to this place where I can enjoy what and how I eat and exercise while simultaneously doing so in a way that treats my body well. 

Don’t miss the forest for the trees. ❤️

Gym Shaming & Gaslighting⁣
⁣
Bullying is not okay. ⁣
Shaming people in the gym is not okay. ⁣
⁣
It’s time we stop tolerating this kind of behavior. ⁣
⁣
I’d love to see more people standing up to and calling out individuals who do this. ⁣
⁣
When someone tells you that they find something you have said or done to be offensive or hurtful, the appropriate response is NOT to tell them they are too sensitive, need thicker skin, need to grow a backbone, or any variation thereof. ⁣
⁣
These are all examples of gaslighting, which is a form of manipulation in which you are made to question your own thoughts, emotions, and sanity. By gaslighting someone who is speaking up against bullying, you are normalizing that kind of behavior. This happens all the time. ⁣
⁣
I’m all for humor. I’ll make fun of myself more than anyone, and anyone who knows me in real life is aware of how goofy I can be. ⁣
⁣
But know when you’ve completely missed the mark. ⁣
⁣
I recently learned that in comedy, there are terms “punching up” and “punching down”. Punching up is generally preferred as the subject matter has more power. When you punch down, you attack people already marginalized and with less power. The video I talked about yesterday entailed punching down. It’s important to know the difference. ⁣
⁣
And if you think it’s okay to mock people in the gym, or arguably worse - actively defend those who do so… take a seat. You’re part of the problem. ⁣
⁣
Be kind… but take no shit. ⁣

Creatine is a substrate that plays a role in energy production by catalyzing adenosine triphosphate (ATP) from creatine and phosphocreatine. 💥

Most people think that the only benefit of creatine supplementation is muscle gain, but this is far from the case. It can also: 
💪increase strength, spring performance, glycogen synthesis, anaerobic threshold, work capacity, and recovery 
🧠improve working memory, cognitive function, and cognitive performance in the face of sleep deprivation 
❤️promote fetal growth, development, and health during pregnancy 
🦴lower cholesterol and triglyceride levels, enhance glycemic control, and minimize bone loss in aging individuals 

and more. 

Vegans and vegetarians may be more likely to respond to creatine supplement as their dietary creatine intake is low. 

Women have 70-80% lower endogenous creatine stores than men, and they also typically consume less dietary creatine. Thus, supplementing with creatine may be helpful to increase endogenous stores. 

You can take 3-5g per day. 

Other common questions I get: 

❓Is it safe?  In recommended doses, yes it is safe. 
❓Can I take this even if my goal is fat loss? 
Yes. 
❓What if I get an upset stomach? 
While the research doesn’t seem to find a causal relationship between creatine intake and digestive upset, anecdotally, I’ve heard of this happening quite a bit. First make sure you are taking the supplement with enough water. Also, splitting up your dose into two halves throughout the day may help. 
❓When’s the best time to take it? 
The research suggests immediately post-workout has a slight advantage to pre-workout ingestion, but take it when you will consistently remember to do so. 
❓Where can I buy creatine? 
I take @pescience creatine capsules, which I find easier to ingest than the powder version. The capsules are not vegan (due to the gelatin in the capsules) but the powder is. “soheefit” saves you 15%

First, let me say that “doing the most” and being as productive as humanly possible is not necessarily the goal. 

Second, I certainly didn’t get to this point overnight. This has been a multiple-year process of fine-tuning my time/energy management skills, respecting my limits, and practicing boundaries. 

With that said, this has worked for me personally: 

👩🏻‍💻I’m very picky about how I spend my time - and more importantly, energy. When I’m working, I’m laser-focused. When I take downtime (which is a crucial component of continuing to show up over the long haul), I fully relax. We got all caught up on Ted Lasso over the weekend, for example, and it was so fun. 
⏰Time blocking: certain times of the workday are devoted to specific tasks. My morning hours are currently reserved for PhD work, and I work on my business in the afternoons and evenings.
🗓I don’t take meetings on Mondays and Fridays. They’re reserved for Tuesdays, Wednesdays, and Thursdays only as much as I can. They are only on an as-needed basis; most communications take place over email and Slack. 
🛌I prioritize my rest. A given task can take me 3-4x longer to get done if I’m feeling tired. Allowing myself to get as much sleep as I need each night puts me in a better mood, plus I’m more creative and more efficient with my work. I understand that getting ample rest like this is a luxury that not everyone has. 
👥Delegate, delegate, delegate. If there’s anything with my work that doesn’t require only me to do, I outsource. This hasn’t always been easy, but I’ve learned over the years that more gets accomplished when you recruit help. 
🙅🏻‍♀️Say no to more things - favors, requests, oftentimes cool opportunities that I want to do but realistically don’t have the capacity for.

tl;dr I’m super intentional about how I spend my time and energies, and I continue to prioritize self-care. 

Lastly, being productive is all fine and well, but please make sure you’re looking after your own mental health and well-being, too. Sometimes the best thing you can do for yourself is to step back. You’re not any less worthy of a human for not constantly being on the achievement path.❤️

#SelfCare #Boundaries

These are the kinds of clients updates I love!

Moving away from rigid dieting mode can be tough. 

That’s why it’s so important to celebrate every little victory. 

What do you notice about these wins? They have nothing to do with the scale; they have nothing to do with your body size. 

They’re far more about repairing your relationship with food, unlearning all the harmful messages you’ve learned from diet culture, and putting your mental health and well-being first. ❤️

Even if you’re not actively pursuing fat loss, it’s entirely possible to still be needlessly restrictive with your diet. That might look like banning certain foods because you think it’s not “healthy” enough, neurotically insisting on adhering to certain macros or calories to the detriment of your well-being, skipping social events because you don’t know how to navigate the food selection, always choosing the lower calorie option, and more. 

And for the record, yes, this is pretty much how I look every time a client shares a win with me. 🥳

An exercise regression refers to a different variation of a given exercise that has decreased demands/difficulty. If you don’t have the strength, mobility, and/or coordination to perform a particular movement, it would make sense to perform a regression.

Many people hear “regression” and think this means that you’re not working as hard or you’re not getting as much out of your training session, but this is NOT the case. It’s important to work within the limits of what you can effectively and safely do. Regression does not mean “worse than” or “inferior to”; it simply means that you’re scaling back an exercise for it to suit you better.

Be sure to master the regression first before you try to advance the exercise. Here are a few examples: 

1️⃣Bulgarian split squat ➡️ split squat 
2️⃣Reverse lunge ➡️ braced reverse lunge 
3️⃣Kneeling leg extension ➡️ band-assisted kneeling leg extension 
4️⃣Push-up ➡️ torso-elevated push-up
5️⃣Deadbug ➡️ legs only, reduced range  of motion 

You should never ever feel bad about your current level of strength, mobility, and/or coordination. Everyone starts somewhere; don’t feel discouraged if you’re not where you want to be right now. ❤️🙂

Wow, @beautifuleatsandthings out here speaking facts! 👏👏👏

I stumbled across her Tiktok page a couple of days ago, and I am absolutely behind this. 

Treating individuals with a higher body weight in a derogatory manner is generally deemed as more socially “acceptable” - but it shouldn’t be. This includes expressing outrage or disgust when someone in a larger body is simply going about their day, enjoying their lives. This is weight stigma, and it’s incredibly harmful. 

You think this kind of treatment is going to help motivate people to eat less? Wrong. Schvey and colleagues (2012) found that weight stigma leads to increased calorie consumption. Tomiyama (2014) describes weight stigma as a “vicious cycle” in which weight stigma begets weight gain. More than that, stigmatizing individuals with overweight and obesity may lead to negative psychological and behavioral consequences - including reduced self-efficacy, increased distress, 

In other words, 𝐬𝐡𝐚𝐦𝐢𝐧𝐠 𝐬𝐨𝐦𝐞𝐨𝐧𝐞 𝐟𝐨𝐫 𝐛𝐞𝐢𝐧𝐠 𝐢𝐧 𝐚 𝐛𝐢𝐠𝐠𝐞𝐫 𝐛𝐨𝐝𝐲 𝐬𝐢𝐳𝐞 𝐝𝐨𝐞𝐬 𝐍𝐎𝐓 𝐡𝐞𝐥𝐩. 

Treat others with respect and compassion, regardless of their body size. 

Thank you again @beautifuleatsandthings for this gem. ❤️

node.text:
Is this scenario familiar to you? 👀 

This used to be me - almost every day, but especially on weekends and special events such as holidays - for years. 🙋🏻‍♀️

Dieting is typically associated with self-imposed boundaries: calorie restrictions, shunning of your favorite chocolate cake, and swearing off your favorite treats for good. The list goes on, and these boundaries vary from one individual to the next, but one theme is common amongst all: "I'm not allowed to eat that."

The “What the Hell Effect,” also known as counterregulatory eating in the scientific literature: once some dietary rule is broken, all hell breaks loose, and you write off the rest of the day, weekend, or even the month as you go overboard on all the foods that were previously forbidden.

Unfortunately, these kinds of dietary restrictions make individuals vulnerable to disinhibiting stimuli such as high-calorie preloads, and you may very well end up eating far more than if you hadn’t kept those foods off-limits in the first place. 

Please note that this is not about whether a cookie is more nutrient-dense than bowl of steaming broccoli. Rather, this is about understanding eating behavior. 

The solution is not to muster up as much willpower as possible; you don’t need more self-control. What you need is to rid yourself of the black-and-white thinking, stop labeling foods as “good” or “bad” and trying to stick to rigid rules that backfire, and adopt a flexible attitude towards foods. 

At the end of the day, it’s important that you’re enjoying the way you eat for long-term consistency. If that means eating a cookie every now and then, I promise you it’s not the end of the world. 🍪❤️

You can do hard things. 

This post is not intended for those of you who push forward no matter what at the expense of your health and well-being. 

This is for those of you who may feel hesitant or afraid to try something because of how difficult it might be - even if it’s ultimately for your own good. 

Stepping into a new gym. 
Applying for that job. 
Leaving an unhealthy, unhappy relationship. 
Going back to school. 
Learning a new skill. 

There’s so much growth that can happen in the best of ways if you’re willing to lean into the discomfort. 

This is something I’ve had to tell myself repeatedly this past week as I started my literature review for my PhD thesis. It’s uncharted territory for me, I have no clue what the heck I’m doing, and yes - I feel pretty petrified. But I remind myself that actually, 𝐈 𝐜𝐚𝐧 𝐝𝐨 𝐡𝐚𝐫𝐝 𝐭𝐡𝐢𝐧𝐠𝐬, and it’s okay to be bad at something before I get good at it, and how proud will I be when I eventually get it published? 

So yes. 

You can do the thing. 
Even if it feels hard. 

❤️

#EatLiftThrive

Out here in my @cropshopboutique as per usual! 💃 I’m wearing the Lauryn Crop and Freedom Shorts 6”, both in size small. “sohee” saves you 10% of your entire order. 

Increasing the range of motion (ROM) on an exercise is one of several techniques you can employ to make a movement more difficult. 
⁣
What I see happening too often, however, is setting up for that extra ROM and then not actually going that full range. This defeats the whole purpose of creating that deficit in the first place. If you’ve positioned yourself on blocks but utilize the same (or less) ROM as before, you may as well perform the standard version instead. ⁣
⁣
In today’s post, I demonstrate this with two common exercises: 
⁣
1️⃣Deficit reverse lunge (or split squat, or Bulgarian split squat): The back knee should either lightly tap the floor or hover just above the floor at the bottom of each repetition. ⁣
2️⃣Deficit push-up: The chest should touch the floor at the bottom of each repetition to be considered full range. ⁣

Please note: there is NOTHING wrong with removing the extra range of motion portion or overall regressing an exercise! 💛 It’s far more important to be implementing exercise variations that you can perform properly and safely than poorly execute a movement your body is not prepared or suited for. 🙈🙌⁣

🫀enhanced cardiovascular health 
💪reversal in specific aging factors in skeletal muscle 
🧠improved cognitive abilities 
💃increased self-esteem and confidence 
😎better quality of life 

There is room for everyone. ❤️

Just because your favorite fitness influencer eats a certain way doesn’t mean you need to copy them 🗣🗣

Please do not blindly emulate the eating or workout regimen of someone else. 

Me? I looooove carbs. Love them. That’s no secret. I feel my best when every meal has potatoes, rice, and/or pasta. 🥔🍚🍝 I also don’t care for breakfast, I like sizable portions of foods, and I could do without snacks. 

But you don’t have to eat this way just because I do. Or that one fitness model does. Or your one super fit friend does. 

There are many, many ways to eat a nutritious, well-rounded diet. 

If you personally don’t really care for carbs and like higher fats - absolutely go for it! 
If you like snacks, snack away. 

Don’t forget the big rocks of nutrition: 
✅adequate calories and protein intake (specific targets will vary according to your goal) 
✅lots of vegetables 
✅variety of fruits
✅mostly nutrient-dense foods 
✅ample hydration 

and honestly, there are a thousand different ways to accomplish the above. 

As a coach, I will always encourage you to eat in a way that makes you feel your best and suits your personal preferences. That’s going to look different from one person to the next. 

Healthy eating does not look one specific way. ❤️

Having the knowledge does not automatically translate to applying that information to your life! 

All the knowledge in the world won’t do anything for you if you’re not putting it to use. 

When it comes to making progress - in any endeavor, truly - what matters far more is what behaviors you’re engaging in on a consistent basis. 

Maybe you’ve convinced yourself that the reason you’re not getting closer to your goal is that you need to learn more. 

And while I am a huge proponent of continuing education, it may very well be the case that you already have all the information you need to succeed. Perhaps what you should shift your focus more towards is doing the damn thing every day. 

More executing. 
More putting in the reps. 
More actually adhering to the right behaviors. 

Do you know someone who could benefit from hearing this? ❤️

node.text:
This is a delicate and nuanced area to try to navigate. As such, I believe this topic deserves to be treated with sensitivity and respect. 

I am fully, fully supportive of people making informed decisions for themselves on how they want their bodies to look.

I do not believe that pursuing fat loss is inherently dangerous. At the same time, I recognize the dangers of diet culture - the norms that glorify thinness and over-restriction around eating. 

It’s a big part of why I don’t post before-and-after weight loss transformation photos, and also why I don’t provide fat loss information indiscriminately on my platform anymore. 

However, if you go into the process with a robust, flexible mindset, with an understanding of the intricacies of the risks involved, and with the proper accountability and support, you may very well come out the other end just fine. 

Can someone intentionally diet and have it be safe? Technically, yes. 
Would I recommend it for YOU? On an individual level, that depends. 

What I would suggest will be different from one person to the next. 

But generally speaking, I am very much an advocate of pursuing health-promoting behaviors. Getting in physical movement on a regular basis, consuming a variety of nutrients, staying hydrated, and managing sleep and stress are all behaviors that I think it’s safe to say would benefit everyone. All of these can happen completely separate from any desire to change the way your body looks. 

There’s a lot that I’ve been learning and no doubt a lot more that I will continue to learn that will further shape my views moving forward. 

Nevertheless, I hope that my stance on this matter is abundantly clear. 

❤️
